Integration refers to âcorrectingâ one or more aspects of two datasets so that differences between them reflect biological and not technical variation.

import scanpy as sc

adata = sc.read_h5ad("db_clustered.h5ad")
bdata = sc.read_h5ad("AJ_annotated_clusters_wt_Feb15.h5ad")
merged = adata.concatenate(bdata, batch_key='dataset', batch_categories=['db','wt'])
sc.pl.umap(merged, color=['leiden','dataset'])
print(f'wt: {bdata.n_obs} cells\ndb: {adata.n_obs} cells\nmerged: {merged.n_obs} cells')
wt: 6551 cells
db: 7318 cells
merged: 13869 cells

The UMAP plot for this merged dataset looks strange. We will need to rerun PCA and rebuild the neighbors graph.

sc.pp.pca(merged)
sc.pp.neighbors(merged)
sc.tl.umap(merged)
sc.pl.umap(merged, color=['leiden','dataset'])

Although these UMAP plots are âfixedâ, they are not âintegratedâ. We will try a few different methods for integration and compare the results to these here to see how they change the representations of the data.
